1
00:00:00,638 --> 00:00:29,852
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:31,806 --> 00:00:37,859
So I thought this evening we'd tackle this crucial role of desire and intention.

3
00:00:38,621 --> 00:00:41,406
So there are three words that we have to be clear about.

4
00:00:43,051 --> 00:00:46,137
Tanha, chanda and chetana.

5
00:00:47,533 --> 00:00:51,299
So now this word, tanha, originally means a drought.

6
00:00:51,679 --> 00:00:58,009
So from that, you get the idea of thirst, and it's used only for unwholesome desires.

7
00:00:58,951 --> 00:01:03,177
And it always is included in dependent origination, right?

8
00:01:03,198 --> 00:01:11,010
In the five middle factors, which are the ones that are a process.

9
00:01:11,159 --> 00:01:14,683
So first of all, you have a contact with one of your sense bases.

10
00:01:15,123 --> 00:01:17,808
Remember the mind, heart is a sense base.

11
00:01:17,828 --> 00:01:25,158
Something has to come up into that base of consciousness, moods, emotions, thoughts, images.

12
00:01:26,459 --> 00:01:31,426
And then there's a relationship to what we are experiencing.

13
00:01:31,566 --> 00:01:36,593
So we give it first of all, excuse me, we give it first of all, a name, a concept.

14
00:01:37,373 --> 00:01:40,018
And then we have a feeling arises with it.

15
00:01:40,066 --> 00:01:45,277
And dependent on those, we have that reaction that we call a desire.

16
00:01:46,058 --> 00:01:52,611
That desire, remember, is coming from a conditioning of wanting and not wanting, right?

17
00:01:52,632 --> 00:01:59,204
And in this case, it's always unwholesome, independent origination, because it describes how we create suffering for ourselves.

18
00:02:00,787 --> 00:02:02,771
And then after that, you have an identity.

19
00:02:03,512 --> 00:02:04,572
I, I want.

20
00:02:05,274 --> 00:02:07,516
And then there's the empowerment.

21
00:02:07,537 --> 00:02:14,385
And that's where we make a distinction between the desire and an intention.

22
00:02:14,847 --> 00:02:15,187
Okay.

23
00:02:17,490 --> 00:02:20,514
So if I take an example, you see an apple.

24
00:02:20,754 --> 00:02:24,239
So the first is just a seeing an object, right?

25
00:02:24,659 --> 00:02:26,222
It's round, et cetera.

26
00:02:26,522 --> 00:02:28,485
And then it's given a name, apple.

27
00:02:28,986 --> 00:02:31,972
And with the word apple, there comes a nice feeling, usually.

28
00:02:33,093 --> 00:02:34,656
And then you might feel hungry.

29
00:02:34,796 --> 00:02:39,965
So there's a desire for the apple, which may come from just ordinary appetite.

30
00:02:39,985 --> 00:02:43,110
But in this case, with tanha, it becomes because we're greedy.

31
00:02:44,132 --> 00:02:45,754
And then you identify with that.

32
00:02:46,215 --> 00:02:48,378
I want that apple.

33
00:02:48,712 --> 00:02:53,479
And you can see there how the language confuses us.

34
00:02:53,579 --> 00:02:57,443
It creates a delusion, gives you the idea that the I comes first.

35
00:02:58,003 --> 00:03:02,750
I want the apple, but actually it comes towards the end of that process.

36
00:03:03,570 --> 00:03:07,795
Once you have that identity, then you empower that desire.

37
00:03:08,296 --> 00:03:12,002
And that's when you become, you become an apple eater.

38
00:03:12,021 --> 00:03:12,342
Okay.

39
00:03:14,902 --> 00:03:16,705
So that's the first word, tan.

40
00:03:17,224 --> 00:03:18,447
The second word is chanda.

41
00:03:18,586 --> 00:03:24,693
Now, actually, in the discourses, chanda can either be wholesome or unwholesome.

42
00:03:25,193 --> 00:03:35,723
But in later Buddhism, the sort of more Abhidhamma commentarial side, the chanda tended to be used only for what was a wholesome desire.

43
00:03:36,185 --> 00:03:44,573
So we do need desire, but we need those desires that lead to liberation, that lead to happiness in this very life.

44
00:03:45,953 --> 00:03:47,415
So that's Chanda.

45
00:03:47,937 --> 00:03:53,586
And we can translate it as a sort of desire.

46
00:03:54,709 --> 00:03:58,175
I mean, you've got to be careful.

47
00:03:58,194 --> 00:04:00,780
These words are so confusing.

48
00:04:01,221 --> 00:04:02,182
A resolution.

49
00:04:02,804 --> 00:04:06,189
It's the it's the energy of wanting something.

50
00:04:08,818 --> 00:04:11,323
Now, I'll tell you where the confusion comes in a minute.

51
00:04:12,283 --> 00:04:14,266
The third word is chaitana.

52
00:04:14,426 --> 00:04:18,994
Now, chaitana is connected to the word citta, which means mind.

53
00:04:19,735 --> 00:04:23,201
So here we're talking about intention or purpose.

54
00:04:24,322 --> 00:04:26,545
So there are these two things.

55
00:04:26,586 --> 00:04:31,333
There's a desire, which can be wholesome and unwholesome, and there's the purpose.

56
00:04:32,242 --> 00:04:40,185
Now, the importance of that is that the desire itself, the actual energy, the wanting, is neutral.

57
00:04:40,726 --> 00:04:46,403
What makes it wholesome and unwholesome is the chaitanya, your purpose for doing something.

58
00:04:50,922 --> 00:05:08,855
Now, to get a feel for what that desire is, as opposed to purpose, you might say, one thing you can do is if you're very hungry, just sit with the food in front of you and just feel the desire.

59
00:05:09,637 --> 00:05:09,757
Right.

60
00:05:09,778 --> 00:05:12,101
So the purpose is obvious.

61
00:05:12,122 --> 00:05:12,903
You want to eat the food.

62
00:05:13,485 --> 00:05:13,605
Right.

63
00:05:13,584 --> 00:05:24,665
But by sitting there, just looking at the food and smelling the aromas and all that, and you can get that feel for what desire is as an energy.

64
00:05:25,065 --> 00:05:25,367
Yeah.

65
00:05:26,122 --> 00:05:33,091
If you want to really experience it, this is what I used to say, but it's been ruined now.

66
00:05:33,632 --> 00:05:37,658
I used to say, turn on the TV when it's your favorite program.

67
00:05:38,199 --> 00:05:42,245
Sorry, sit in front of the TV when it's your favorite program and don't turn it on.

68
00:05:42,925 --> 00:05:46,009
But unfortunately, I, a player, has ruined all that.

69
00:05:48,153 --> 00:05:50,136
You know, you can always catch up with a bit of a pain.

70
00:05:50,696 --> 00:05:51,237
Never mind.

71
00:05:54,119 --> 00:06:04,550
So if we take an example from, say, physics of throwing a stone, the energy within the arm is translated into the stone or transferred into the stone, rather.

72
00:06:05,572 --> 00:06:08,855
And you cannot separate the force from the stone, right?

73
00:06:08,875 --> 00:06:12,959
You can't stop it in midair and say, well, look, this is the force and this is the stone.

74
00:06:13,500 --> 00:06:14,901
They're all one.

75
00:06:15,283 --> 00:06:17,845
But the purpose of throwing the stone can be various.

76
00:06:17,865 --> 00:06:22,911
So when I'm walking around the property here, some of the stones from the...

77
00:06:22,891 --> 00:06:25,482
car park have come onto the path where they shouldn't be.

78
00:06:25,882 --> 00:06:29,338
So I might just pick one up and flick it back onto the car park.

79
00:06:29,437 --> 00:06:30,201
Yeah.

80
00:06:30,399 --> 00:06:36,589
I might find a flat stone, we have a little pond, and I might throw it on the pond to see it skim just for the joy of it.

81
00:06:38,012 --> 00:06:39,394
But then we also have rabbits.

82
00:06:39,555 --> 00:06:52,456
Now, most of you or some of you will remember my, what can we say, my experience with moles and how we had to get rid of the lawns and create a garden.

83
00:06:53,117 --> 00:06:56,862
So now we have rabbits who come in and dig little holes.

84
00:06:56,843 --> 00:07:09,298
So I might be tempted to pick up a stone, not to harm the rabbit, you understand, but to give it the impression that it shouldn't actually be digging a hole in the garden and they've got a whole meadow to go and do it in.

85
00:07:10,800 --> 00:07:22,995
So these are what you might say, you're in my intentions, but the actual energy or the desire to throw the stone is neutral, right?

86
00:07:23,014 --> 00:07:24,437
There's a distinction there.

87
00:07:26,543 --> 00:07:28,225
And the Buddha makes it quite clear.

88
00:07:28,365 --> 00:07:36,482
He says, I say to you that it is the chaitanya that creates a kamma.

89
00:07:37,002 --> 00:07:43,394
Now, kamma here is not the same as karma, which has come into our language as comeuppance and what you deserve.

90
00:07:43,956 --> 00:07:46,019
Kamma here just means an action.

91
00:07:46,355 --> 00:07:50,199
Now remember that when you repeat an action, you create a habit.

92
00:07:51,119 --> 00:07:57,064
And as we know, a collection of habits is your personality, your character.

93
00:07:57,444 --> 00:08:00,468
And once you've got that, then your destiny is assured.

94
00:08:01,028 --> 00:08:06,954
So something is driving us to our destiny and it's these habits that we've collected throughout life.

95
00:08:07,074 --> 00:08:07,675
Yeah.

96
00:08:07,694 --> 00:08:15,601
And our purpose of course, is to discern those habits that lead us to perdition and those habits that lead to liberation.

97
00:08:17,877 --> 00:08:21,884
I'll give you another example, actually, which comes from the Vinaya, the rule of the monks.

98
00:08:22,985 --> 00:08:42,197
If, for instance, I see somebody's mobile and I'm very attracted to it, and I think to myself, I'd like that mobile, because they've left it unguarded on a piece of furniture or something.

99
00:08:42,835 --> 00:08:50,966
Now, if I just allow the thoughts to process, in a sense, I'm building up a wrong intention.

100
00:08:51,567 --> 00:09:02,261
Now, it might be that this intention becomes so strong that I actually move towards the mobile with the intention at the back of my mind to slip it in my pocket.

101
00:09:02,528 --> 00:09:04,875
Now, and then I stop myself.

102
00:09:05,076 --> 00:09:06,359
I stop myself in that process.

103
00:09:06,419 --> 00:09:07,403
What the heck's going on?

104
00:09:07,582 --> 00:09:09,950
So this is called a dukkata.

105
00:09:10,049 --> 00:09:13,922
This is already a small offense.

106
00:09:14,543 --> 00:09:15,626
It's not serious.

107
00:09:16,282 --> 00:09:24,557
However, the desire for this mobile overtakes me and I again approach the mobile and I just put my hand on it.

108
00:09:25,219 --> 00:09:28,664
And then in a sort of horror, I take it back.

109
00:09:29,727 --> 00:09:32,052
Now, this is what's called a Gardevoir.

110
00:09:32,091 --> 00:09:33,033
It's a serious offence.

111
00:09:33,595 --> 00:09:38,965
I've actually gone and touched the object that I'm wanting.

112
00:09:40,361 --> 00:09:43,910
But again, the desire for this mobile completely overtakes me.

113
00:09:44,131 --> 00:09:44,812
I go to it.

114
00:09:45,193 --> 00:09:49,325
I touch it and I move it a nano centimeter.

115
00:09:49,345 --> 00:09:51,149
That's all just a nano centimeter.

116
00:09:51,529 --> 00:09:53,153
I suddenly realize what I've done.

117
00:09:53,514 --> 00:09:57,004
I drop it and I walk away too late.

118
00:09:56,984 --> 00:10:02,051
As far as the Vinaya is concerned, I've committed an act of stealing, even if I don't get it.

119
00:10:02,591 --> 00:10:03,513
It's an act of stealing.

120
00:10:03,894 --> 00:10:06,476
And in the Vinaya, this is a very serious offense.

121
00:10:07,418 --> 00:10:09,240
It's called a Parajika.

122
00:10:09,260 --> 00:10:18,333
So Parajika translates as end of life, which means that you have to leave the order and you can't join it again in this lifetime.

123
00:10:18,313 --> 00:10:33,113
So this shows you the, there's an example to sort of show the process of how we can unwittingly be developing a desire, which then suddenly grabs us and we do something that, you know, we ought not to have done.

124
00:10:36,017 --> 00:10:38,581
So the model there is don't become a monastic.

125
00:10:41,104 --> 00:10:44,288
So one or two things here now, just as a sort of reflection.

126
00:10:45,769 --> 00:10:51,557
When we have a negative desire, so this is to do with a sense of self, yeah?

127
00:10:51,576 --> 00:10:58,706
When we have a negative desire, when we're doing something or saying something, there's always a separation, right?

128
00:10:58,765 --> 00:11:05,955
You create a duality between the person who doesn't want to do something and what you're actually doing.

129
00:11:05,934 --> 00:11:09,541
So a simple example might be, you know, washing pots.

130
00:11:09,561 --> 00:11:18,837
You're fed up with washing pots, especially if you've got a family and all these pots and pans everywhere and you're fed up with it and you're washing the pots.

131
00:11:18,857 --> 00:11:24,307
Now yourself, the sense of self is I don't, I shouldn't be doing this.

132
00:11:25,048 --> 00:11:28,634
You know, somebody else should be doing this and I'm fed up with doing this.

133
00:11:28,615 --> 00:11:31,357
and you're washing the pots at the same time, right?

134
00:11:31,739 --> 00:11:36,384
So there's a split there between the sense of self and what you're actually doing.

135
00:11:36,783 --> 00:11:44,033
And that's why sometimes you lose your attention and you drop a pot and break it, and then you're really mad, see?

136
00:11:44,913 --> 00:11:53,644
Now, if you have a positive craving, if you have something that you really want, an indulging thing,

137
00:11:54,568 --> 00:12:01,337
then here you would immerse, you can immerse completely into that experience.

138
00:12:01,357 --> 00:12:07,445
So it might be that you're very fond of horror movies or something like that.

139
00:12:07,926 --> 00:12:11,190
And you're knowing yourself that perhaps you shouldn't be watching these.

140
00:12:11,470 --> 00:12:13,913
I'm not saying you shouldn't, you're saying it to yourself.

141
00:12:14,474 --> 00:12:19,259
And then you absorb into the film, you lose yourself into the film.

142
00:12:20,539 --> 00:12:27,701
Now, the problem with going into something from a position of indulgence is that you go in with prejudice.

143
00:12:28,283 --> 00:12:29,166
For instance,

144
00:12:30,715 --> 00:12:31,956
And it's selective.

145
00:12:32,937 --> 00:12:39,604
So for instance, supposing now you go to a restaurant and there's a pizza, right?

146
00:12:40,264 --> 00:12:42,027
So you've had all these pizzas.

147
00:12:42,047 --> 00:12:47,111
So you've got this idea of what a proper pizza ought to be, okay?

148
00:12:47,192 --> 00:12:53,938
And you walk into the restaurant, you ask for a pizza and it just doesn't live up to what you expect a pizza to be.

149
00:12:54,299 --> 00:12:58,443
So you're very disappointed and you eat it, of course, grumbling.

150
00:12:58,423 --> 00:13:02,769
And you won't go back, of course.

151
00:13:03,370 --> 00:13:07,715
But if this was the first pizza you'd ever eaten, you'd be delighted by it.

152
00:13:09,956 --> 00:13:17,426
Another thing is when you are eating something like sticky toffee pudding, right?

153
00:13:17,446 --> 00:13:23,773
So if you eat sticky toffee pudding and what you really want is the sweetness of it,

154
00:13:23,855 --> 00:13:34,187
So you're prejudiced towards, you're biased towards tasting the sweetness of the sticky toffee pudding.

155
00:13:34,849 --> 00:13:39,875
Now, it might have all sorts of different subtle flavors, but you're unaware of those.

156
00:13:39,934 --> 00:13:43,679
You've brushed them out, as it were, because all you're interested in is sweetness.

157
00:13:44,480 --> 00:13:47,445
And that's what indulgence does.

158
00:13:47,625 --> 00:13:52,191
It just looks for what will gratify it.

159
00:13:52,407 --> 00:13:57,875
So, for instance, another distinction would be, say, wine tasters or tea tasters, better.

160
00:14:00,457 --> 00:14:10,753
They have to put the tea or the wine on the tongue and roll it round and really be aware of all the tastes that come out from that.

161
00:14:10,783 --> 00:14:16,251
Whereas when we drink tea normally, we just have this one taste in mind.

162
00:14:16,732 --> 00:14:18,735
And if there isn't enough milk, we don't like it.

163
00:14:18,796 --> 00:14:23,023
If there's not enough sugar, if it's not strong enough and so on and so forth.

164
00:14:23,043 --> 00:14:33,619
So it's a case of recognizing that whenever we're doing something from a position of indulgence, it's always going to crimp our experience.

165
00:14:33,739 --> 00:14:34,059
That's all.

166
00:14:34,080 --> 00:14:35,442
It's going to limit it.

167
00:14:36,197 --> 00:14:52,321
Apart from, of course, creating a further, greater dependency on it, like they become addictions at various levels or other, because you're always trying to satisfy this indulgence.

168
00:14:53,222 --> 00:14:56,366
And the fact of the matter is it can't be satisfied.

169
00:14:57,325 --> 00:14:59,727
Because that's not where the suffering is coming from.

170
00:15:00,349 --> 00:15:06,135
The suffering is coming from some sense of lack within us, some sense of neediness within us.

171
00:15:06,736 --> 00:15:14,386
And the object that we're using to fulfill it can never cure that sense of neediness, right?

172
00:15:14,407 --> 00:15:17,110
It just gratifies it for a little while.

173
00:15:17,650 --> 00:15:22,977
The only way we can cure the neediness is by staying with it until it evaporates.

174
00:15:23,346 --> 00:15:27,692
And the energy of that habit is slowly undermined and disappears.

175
00:15:28,452 --> 00:15:37,183
So looking to indulge ourselves, hoping to get rid of the sense, hoping to get rid of that craving is a non-starter.

176
00:15:37,403 --> 00:15:38,424
It just gets worse.

177
00:15:43,471 --> 00:15:45,573
Okay, so...

178
00:15:48,085 --> 00:15:52,995
Now, going back to chaitanya, remember that that's your conditioning factor.

179
00:15:53,076 --> 00:15:59,631
The purpose for which we're doing something is actually reinforcing a habit that we already have.

180
00:16:00,413 --> 00:16:03,681
So it's really important to catch that purpose.

181
00:16:03,660 --> 00:16:15,220
Now, sometimes in the discourses, remember that the word chanda, desire, will be used in a sense of wholesome and unwholesome.

182
00:16:15,860 --> 00:16:25,197
But don't be confused by that if you come across it, because it's always the purpose for which we're doing something which is conditioning us.

183
00:16:26,341 --> 00:16:36,801
Just one little example, which comes from the Visuddhimagga, the path of purification, which was written by a monk called Buddhaghosa in the 5th century.

184
00:16:37,442 --> 00:16:40,467
And it's got to be one of the great spiritual manuals of the world.

185
00:16:40,589 --> 00:16:45,918
I mean, in that book, which is a big tome, and it's as dry as you could imagine.

186
00:16:45,899 --> 00:17:00,136
It has a whole section on the Dharma, a whole section on how to develop beautiful mental states, such as the use of love and metta and things like that, and a whole section on how to develop insight.

187
00:17:00,638 --> 00:17:02,119
So it's a really beautiful book.

188
00:17:02,139 --> 00:17:07,306
And in it, he gives this example of a teacher who's with his students.

189
00:17:07,926 --> 00:17:14,454
And while he's talking, his hand lifts up and he stops and very slowly puts his hand down.

190
00:17:14,536 --> 00:17:16,479
And all the students want to know what happened there.

191
00:17:16,499 --> 00:17:18,622
He said, well, what happened?

192
00:17:19,063 --> 00:17:21,205
And he said, I didn't know my intention.

193
00:17:22,067 --> 00:17:32,702
In other words, his mindfulness is so acute, is so in the present moment that even the smallest intention would normally be acknowledged.

194
00:17:33,403 --> 00:17:34,926
And in this case, he hadn't.

195
00:17:35,406 --> 00:17:37,490
But he recognized that his hand shouldn't be there.

196
00:17:37,851 --> 00:17:39,232
And he very slowly put it back.

197
00:17:39,753 --> 00:17:42,518
He intended to put his hand back where it ought to be.

198
00:17:43,357 --> 00:17:47,846
So that's how awake we can become in daily life.

199
00:17:48,346 --> 00:17:54,637
And it's especially important to be awake whenever we're making decisions that are of an ethical nature.

200
00:17:57,762 --> 00:18:03,492
OK, so finally, this Chanda, just going back to Chanda.

201
00:18:05,244 --> 00:18:16,299
is a desire which grows with the habit of doing something until it becomes a sort of zeal.

202
00:18:16,339 --> 00:18:20,586
And it becomes part of the four bases of power or success.

203
00:18:21,086 --> 00:18:24,731
And I've covered that in an earlier Moon presentation.

204
00:18:25,894 --> 00:18:27,115
And that's your zeal.

205
00:18:27,174 --> 00:18:31,961
And with it, there comes the energy to support that aspiration.

206
00:18:32,431 --> 00:18:36,998
And then there's the commitment, the devotion of the heart to what you're doing.

207
00:18:37,478 --> 00:18:50,877
And finally, in terms of anything that needs an investigation, the path of insight, there comes that discrimination, that investigation of what we're experiencing.

208
00:18:51,459 --> 00:18:57,627
OK, so this chanda moves from being the slightest

209
00:18:57,777 --> 00:19:06,987
the slightest little desire, good desire in this case, to a real zeal, a real desire to achieve something.

210
00:19:07,106 --> 00:19:09,153
And that's your chanda.

211
00:19:10,315 --> 00:19:23,876
Okay, so just to sum up very quickly, we've got these three words, this tanha, which is any desire which we can perceive or realize is unwholesome, chanda, which is a desire which is wholesome.

212
00:19:24,919 --> 00:19:31,269
And what we have to be careful of is this cetana, the purpose for which we're doing something.

213
